### By-election Results

By-elections are often more revealing than scheduled contests. They are the whispers of discontent, the sudden shifts in local sentiment, the moments when a single seat changes hands.

#### 1995–1999

*   **Forest By-Election, 31 October 1996:** An [Independent](/Independent_(politician)) candidate secured a narrow victory over the [Conservatives](/Conservative_Party_(UK)), marking an [Independent](/Independent_(politician)) gain from the [Liberal Democrats](/Liberal_Democrats_(UK)). A swing of 2.6% was enough to flip the seat. Turnout was a modest 30.8%.
*   **Roade By-Election, 2 October 1997:** [Labour](/Labour_Party_(UK)) held onto the seat with a significant swing of +12.7%, increasing their majority against the [Conservatives](/Conservative_Party_(UK)). Turnout was a rather dismal 21.5%.
*   **Bugbrooke By-Election, 4 December 1997:** The [Conservatives](/Conservative_Party_(UK)) held this seat comfortably, with no discernible swing indicated in the provided data. Turnout was 22.1%.
*   **Deanshanger By-Election, 2 July 1998:** [Labour](/Labour_Party_(UK)) managed to hold this seat, despite a slight decrease in their vote share (-2.6%). The [Conservatives](/Conservative_Party_(UK)) saw a substantial increase (+29.2%), indicating a tightening race. Turnout was 22.1%.

#### 1999–2003

*   **Courteenhall By-Election, 7 June 2001:** In a complex result, the [Conservatives](/Conservative_Party_(UK)) held the seat, but with a significant reduction in their vote share (-25.0%). [Labour](/Labour_Party_(UK)) also lost ground, while an [Independent](/Independent_(politician)) candidate and the [Liberal Democrats](/Liberal_Democrats_(UK)) made gains. A 7.1% majority was maintained.
*   **Middleton Cheney By-Election, 7 June 2001:** A significant [Conservative](/Conservative_Party_(UK)) gain from [Labour](/Labour_Party_(UK)), with a swing of +11.3% to the Conservatives. Turnout was 26.0%.
*   **Yardley By-Election, 7 June 2001:** Another [Conservative](/Conservative_Party_(UK)) gain from [Labour](/Labour_Party_(UK)), this time with a +8.6% swing. The Conservatives held a commanding 31.0% majority.
*   **Salcey By-Election, 4 October 2001:** The [Conservatives](/Conservative_Party_(UK)) held this seat with a small gain of +3.0%. [Labour](/Labour_Party_(UK)) saw a corresponding decrease. Turnout was a low 20.5%.

#### 2003–2007

*   **Courteenhall By-Election, 25 September 2003:** &#91;14&#93; The [Conservatives](/Conservative_Party_(UK)) held this seat, increasing their vote share by 9.9% and securing a substantial 34.4% majority. The [Liberal Democrats](/Liberal_Democrats_(UK)) also saw gains, while [Labour](/Labour_Party_(UK)) lost ground. Turnout was 23.0%.
*   **Cogenhoe By-Election, 14 July 2005:** &#91;15&#93; An [Independent](/Independent_(politician)) candidate achieved a gain from the [Conservatives](/Conservative_Party_(UK)), demonstrating the potential for local candidates to disrupt the established party order. The [Labour](/Labour_Party_(UK)) vote share remained minimal. Turnout was 24.6%.

#### 2007–2011

*   **Grange Park By-Election, 12 February 2009:** &#91;16&#93; The [Conservatives](/Conservative_Party_(UK)) held this seat with a significant majority of 52.1%. The [Liberal Democrats](/Liberal_Democrats_(UK)) saw a considerable increase in their vote share (+23.9%), indicating a shift in local allegiances. Turnout was a low 19.2%.

#### 2011–2015

*   **Towcester Brook By-Election, 9 February 2012:** &#91;17&#93; A notable [Liberal Democrats](/Liberal_Democrats_(UK)) gain from the [Conservatives](/Conservative_Party_(UK)), with a swing of +15.5% to the Liberal Democrats. They secured a strong 28.6% majority. [UKIP](/UK_Independence_Party) also registered a presence. Turnout was 29.3%.
*   **Grange Park By-Election, 28 June 2012:** &#91;18&#93; The [Conservatives](/Conservative_Party_(UK)) held this seat, with only a marginal change in vote share. Turnout was 13.4%, a notably low figure.
*   **Grange Park By-Election, 2 October 2014 (2 seats):** &#91;19&#93; The [Conservatives](/Conservative_Party_(UK)) successfully held both seats in this by-election. The results showed [Labour](/Labour_Party_(UK)) and [UKIP](/UK_Independence_Party) also competing for the seats.

#### 2015–2021

*   **Old Stratford By-Election, 22 September 2016:** &#91;20&#93; The [Conservatives](/Conservative_Party_(UK)) retained this seat, with [UKIP](/UK_Independence_Party) as the main challenger. Turnout was 22.2%.
*   **Grange Park By-Election, 1 December 2016:** &#91;21&#93; The [Conservatives](/Conservative_Party_(UK)) held this seat, despite a decrease in their vote share. [Labour](/Labour_Party_(UK)) and [UKIP](/UK_Independence_Party) also contested the seat, with the [Green](/Green_Party_of_England_and_Wales) party making an appearance. Turnout was 19.8%.
*   **Kings Sutton By-Election, 4 May 2017:** &#91;22&#93; The [Conservatives](/Conservative_Party_(UK)) held this seat, with a swing of +4.2% to them, against [Labour](/Labour_Party_(UK)). Turnout was 33.1%.
*   **Middleton Cheney By-Election, 12 April 2018:** &#91;23&#93; A complex result saw the [Conservatives](/Conservative_Party_(UK)) hold the seat, but with a significant loss of vote share (-21.6%). The [Liberal Democrats](/Liberal_Democrats_(UK)) saw a dramatic increase (+34.1%), indicating a strong local push. [Labour](/Labour_Party_(UK)) and the [Green](/Green_Party_of_England_and_Wales) party also contested. Turnout was 40.7%.
*   **Astwell By-Election, 21 June 2018:** &#91;24&#93; The [Conservatives](/Conservative_Party_(UK)) held this seat with a stable majority. [Labour](/Labour_Party_(UK)) saw a slight increase in their vote share. Turnout was 19.5%.
*   **Whittlewood By-Election, 21 June 2018:** &#91;25&#93; A significant gain for the [Liberal Democrats](/Liberal_Democrats_(UK)) from the [Conservatives](/Conservative_Party_(UK)). The Liberal Democrats secured a 20.1% majority. Turnout was 30.0%.
*   **Middleton Cheney By-Election, 12 September 2019:** &#91;26&#93; The [Liberal Democrats](/Liberal_Democrats_(UK)) gained this seat from the [Conservatives](/Conservative_Party_(UK)), with a swing of +9.7% to the Liberal Democrats. They held a narrow majority of 4.4%. The [Green](/Green_Party_of_England_and_Wales) party also saw gains. Turnout was 40.2%.

These by-elections paint a picture of a fluctuating local political landscape. While the Conservatives often held their ground, there were clear opportunities for other parties, particularly the Liberal Democrats in later years, to make inroads. The presence of [UKIP](/UK_Independence_Party) and the [Green Party](/Green_Party_of_England_and_Wales) also indicates a diversifying political spectrum at the local level.

